1 Bar charts

Bar charts provide a useful alternative way of presenting a set of values associated with the levels of a factor.

  1. Bar charts can be used for values other than proportions.

  2. Bar charts use position on a common scale to encode their values.

  3. This means they provide a better way of delivering information than pie charts.

Important-distinction: be aware of when making bar graphs: sometimes the bar heights represent counts of cases in the data set, and sometimes they represent values in the data set.

Pseudo Data Dot Chart

pseudo<-data.frame(x=c(23,43,54,25,12))
row.names(pseudo)<-c("A","B","C","D","E")
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
graphics::barplot(pseudo$x, main="Pseudo Bar Chart")
grid.table(pseudo)

stacked

datum<-data.frame(x1=c(23,43,54,25,12),x2=c("F","F","M","F","M"),x3=c(2,3,3,1,3))
row.names(datum)<-c("A","B","C","D","E")
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
graphics::barplot(table(datum$x2,datum$x3), main="Pseudo Stacked Bar Chart")
grid.table(table(datum$x2,datum$x3))

** grouped**

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
graphics::barplot(table(datum$x2,datum$x3), beside=T, main="Pseudo Grouped Bar Chart")
grid.table(table(datum$x2,datum$x3))

2.1 Simple Bar Chart

barplot(d1, main = "Simple Bar Chart")

play with arguments

barplot(d1, main = "Simple Bar Chart", xlab = "Improvement", ylab = "Frequency", width = 3)

barplot(d1, main = "Simple Bar Chart", xlab = "Improvement", ylab = "Frequency", width = 3, xlim=c(0,20)) # length no visible without xlim

barplot(d1, main = "Bar Chart", xlab = "Improvement", ylab = "Frequency", col = "lightblue")

barplot(d1, main = "Bar Chart", xlab = "Improvement", ylab = "Frequency", col = hcl(seq(0, 240, by = 60))) # tricolored

barplot(d1, main = "Bar Chart", xlab = "Improvement", ylab = "Frequency", col = hcl(seq(0, 240, by = 60)), names.arg = c("A", "B", "C")) #change labels

barplot(d1, main = "Treatment Outcome", horiz = TRUE, cex.names = 0.8, cex.main = 1.2, las = 1, xlim = c(0,50), names.arg = c("No Improvement", "Some Improvement","Marked Improvement"))

barplot(d1, main="Horizontal Bar Plot",xlab="Improvement", ylab = "Frequency",horiz=T,col=c("blue","red","green"))

If the categorical variable to be plotted is a factor or ordered factor, you can create a vertical bar plot quickly with the plot() function. Arthritis$Improved is a factor:

is.factor(Arthritis$Improved)
## [1] TRUE
plot(Arthritis$Improved, main = "Bar Plot", xlab="Improved", ylab = "Frequency")

plot(Arthritis$Improved, horiz = TRUE, main = "Column Plot",xlab = "Frequency", ylab = "Improved")

A stacked percent bar plot

library(RColorBrewer)
coul = brewer.pal(3, "Pastel2") 
 
#Transform this data in %
data_percentage=apply(d2, 2, function(x){x*100/sum(x,na.rm=T)})
 
# Make a stacked barplot--> it will be in %!
barplot(data_percentage, col=coul , border="white", xlab="group")

barplot(prop.table(d2),col=coul)

values <- c(1, 2, 5, 4)
errors <- c(0.25, 0.5, 0.33, 0.12)
names <- paste("Trial", 1:4)
sig <- c("a", "a", "b", "b")
dynamitePlot(values, errors)

par(mar = c(3, 5, 1, 1) + .1)
dynamitePlot(values, errors, names.arg = names, significance = sig,
    ylab = "Values", sym = TRUE, cex.lab = 1.5, cex.axis = 1.2,
    cex.names = 1.2, cex.sig = 1.5, space = c(0, 0.2, 0.8, 0.2),
    lwd = 2, head = 0, col = c(grey(0.5), "white"), border = c(NA,
        "black"))
